passages.text: Equity Research August 29, 2025

Our August look at the Travel & Leisure sector sews together data from multiple Analyst teams and sub- sectors to surface trends & insights. Cruise lines remain the strongest vertical, with pricing accelerating through the summer. Elsewhere, Theme Parks had a good July, with web visits and app user activity rising, while US Hotel RevPAR continues to slide, though it'll trends have held up.

Travel Verticals Are All Linked and Driven by Labor Market HealthIn the following charts we show the degree to which the travel ecosystem is tightly linked, with airlines, hotels, and car rental companies all somewhat inter- dependent on each other, and all three verticals dependent on the health of the labor market to drive both leisure and business demand. To these points, we highlight the \(0.9+\) correlations between airline, hotel, and car rental volumes over the last decade, as well as the \((0.7)+\) correlations between those same volumes and US unemployment over several decades.

Given the relatively strong inverse correlation between travel volumes and unemployment, we are keeping a close eye on the US employment situation. While current unemployment levels are relatively benign vs. historical levels, forward indicators of labor market health are highlighting risks that unemployment may rise into the late summer and fall, putting pressure on travel volumes this year and potentially next.

Hotel Purchase Intentions Weakening; U.S. RevPAR Trends Get Progressively Worse. For Hotels, we note that purchase intentions rose slightly at WH, while trends declined at MAR, HLT, H, and CHH. Per Kalibri, US Hotel RevPAR fell (4.6%) Y/Y in July, which follows declines of (2.1%) and (1.7%) Y/Y in June and May, respectively. We note that for July, RevPAR was again down Y/Y at every chainscale except Luxury (+0.8%), with Upper Upscale seeing trends down \(\sim 4\%\) Y/Y and every other chainscale seeing RevPAR down \(\sim 6\%\) Y/Y.

International hotel spending trends strengthened in July: Worldwide hotel spending growth in July accelerated 2 pts sequentially to \(+7\%\) y/y, driven by a 1 pt improvement in Room Night growth to \(+4\%\) y/y and a 1 pt acceleration in ADR growth to \(+3\%\) y/y. Each global region except Latin America experienced faster growth, led by the Middle East / Africa (+9 pts sequentially) and Europe (+4 pts). North America and APAC spending growth improved 1 pt sequentially, while LatAm was unchanged. The broad improvement in spending growth substantiates commentary from ABNB/BKNG/EXPE at 2Q earnings, which indicated stable/improving demand trends in July. Encouragingly, spending growth in Europe reached its fastest pace since August '24 if Germany and Israel are excluded from the regional total, which we think is appropriate given the 2024 European football championship in Germany (hosted 6/14/24- 7/14/24) and ongoing Middle East tensions are distorting comparisons. Faster growth in Europe suggests ABNB/BKNG are well- positioned to capture international momentum, given Europe represents \(\sim 40\% /50\%\) of total Nights for each.
See our latest hotel trends report for more detail.

For Cruise, purchase intentions took a big step down in July, particularly at CCL (which we hypothesize is related to the release of Netflix's "Poop Cruise" on June 24th), though RCL and DIS saw at least partial recovery in August. Our look at advertised pricing indicates that pricing trends as of July were strong, with DIS and VIK seeing the biggest increases. To this point, in July, advertised pricing was up 1.8%, 1.7%, 0.5%, 0.2%, and 0.2% M/M at DIS, VIK, CCL, RCL, and NCLH, respectively, while MSC was flat M/M and LIND was down (1.4%) M/M.

Web traffic and app data for the category continued to improve, with category web visits up 16% Y/Y, the highest in 15 months. RCL with web visits up 25% Y/Y drove the bulk of the category, but all lines we track improved y/y in July vs. June. For App usage, RCL was also the leader, with all lines up at least 25% Y/Y.

US Theme Park trends improved in July from June, with category web visits up 4% Y/Y from flat in June, and App users up 18% Y/Y from 15% in June. Universal Orlando and its new Epic Universe theme park again led the category, but notably Six Flags, SeaWorld, and Busch Gardens all saw stronger app downloads and user trends in July as well, with app users up 17%, 34%, and 52%, respectively. Growth at Disney lagged the group, but Orlando Disney World trends did also improve in July from June as competition from the second full month of the Epic Universe opening is shifting to an Orlando traffic tailwind. Disney World web visits were down -8% Y/Y in July vs. -11% in June, and app users grew +4%Y/Y vs. -6% in June.
Exhibit 16 - U.S. Theme Park y/y Change in Web Visits and App Usage
Source: Similar Web, Listen First, Sensor Tower, Jefferies

In July, US inbound travel weakness continued, as overseas traveler arrivals (excludes Canada, Mexico) declined \(- 3\%\) Y/Y, a \(\sim 4\) ppts decel. from 2Q. July's implied 3Q decel. directionally aligns with V/MA's ex- intra- Europe cross- border volume growth, which has continued to drift lower, and is implied to decel in 3Q based on July growth.

Canada - US inbound traveler border crossings growth held steady in July, but remains weak, declining \(- 18\%\) Y/Y in July after declining \(- 18\%\) Y/Y in 2Q and \(- 17.5\%\) Y/Y in June. Mexico - US inbound traveler border crossings declined \(- 4\%\) Y/Y, a \(\sim 2\) ppts decel. from 2Q, and a \(\sim 0.5\) ppts decel. from June.

Both V & MA have downplayed their risk / exposure to US inbound travel, with MA sharing that no single country corridor composes \(>3\%\) of cross- border volume. We est. total US inbound travel represents \(\sim 10\%\) of V/MA cross- border ex intra- Europe volume.

North American Scheduled Flights Down \(5\%\) vs 2019. We count 197,736 flights in North America for the most recent week, which is \(+1\%\) y- oy, to \(5\%\) below 2019. This is tied to US flights \(- 4\%\) relative to 2019, or up \(1\%\) y- oy, driven by the domestic side \(- 5\%\) \((+1\%\) y- oy), with international flights \(+2\%\) \((+4\%\) y- oy). Scheduled flight data supports the Morning Consult survey (Exhibit 14) showing muted air travel intentions in August. Notably, the data captures scheduled flights rather than flown flights, so close- in cancelations where the flight was not removed from the official schedule will not be captured.

Global Web Traffic by Location of Airline \(+3\%\) Y/Y In Week Beginning August 15. Among US carriers, average TRASMs declined \(\sim 3\%\) y- oy in Q2, including AAL/DAL/LUV all \(- 3\%\) with UAL the laggard down \(4\%\) in the quarter. Looking ahead, AAL implied unit revenues drop another \(2 - 4\%\) y- oy, w/DAL close at \(- 2\%\) , while LUV has a wider range from \(- 2\%\) to \(+2\%\) y- oy in Q3. The Present Situation Index fell 1.6pts to 131.2, while the Expectations Index fell 1.2pts to 74.8, still below the 80 threshold for the seventh consecutive month, suggesting a recession is anticipated. The latest week's web traffic data, may suggest an increase in air travel, with global airline and OTA web traffic by customer location \(+5\%\) y- oy, although the US lagged \(- 2\%\) y- oy. In terms of app traffic, unique app users are up \(12\%\) y- oy and \(+5\%\) on a T3M basis.

First and Business Class Travel Sentiment Up \(28.0\%\) Y/Y and Up \(46.5\%\) vs 2019. Our survey asked \(\sim 6,800\) respondents if they have flown first or business class \(2+\) times in the past year. In August, the net index score for premium travel fell to 62.9, down \(4\%\) from July, up \(28.0\%\) Y/Y, and \(+46.5\%\) vs August 2019 aligning with resilient luxury lodging trends (Exhibit 25). This compares to the historical average score of 54.1, and the peak score of 71.4 in April 2021, and trough score of 42.9 in May 2019.

On the travel front, we track both domestic and international trends due to their strong correlation with revenue: U.S. citizens originating travel is 0.83 and 0.83 correlated with HTZ and CAR revenue, respectively. Additionally, foreign originating travel is 0.86 and 0.84 correlated with HTZ and CAR international revenue. July's data showed a Y/Y decline, with foreign- originating travel down approximately \(\sim 7\%\) Y/Y, but up \(20\%\) MoM. That said, US citizens originating was up \(6\%\) YoY but down \(3\%\) MoM. Turning to business exposure, when looking at business and leisure splits, we note that both companies' splits are relatively similar with CAR's business revenue at \(65\%\) and HTZ Americas's at \(64\%\) .

All in, we anticipate 3Q revenue flattish Y/Y and down \(9\%\) Y/Y for CAR and HTZ, respectively, driven by lower pricing and fewer rental/transaction days. Note, car rental revenue is highly correlated with airline passenger revenue and our airline team sees airline travel intentions as down to slightly improved for leisure and corporate travelers. Specifically, \(52\%\) of leisure travelers plans to travel in the next 6 months down from \(56\%\) as of July. However, \(23\%\) of corporate travelers plan to travel in the next 6 months, slightly improved from \(22\%\) . HTZ's and CAR'S revenue are .83 and .80 correlated with Delta passenger revenue. For CAR, we anticipate RPD (pricing) to be down \(\sim 1\%\) Y/Y and rental days (volume) to be up \(\sim 2\%\) . Likewise, at HTZ, we anticipate RPD to be down \(5\%\) and transaction days (volume) to be down \(\sim 4\%\) . Note, we anticipate pricing to be more pressured than normal driven by recalls which impact the mix of vehicles. Said another way, vehicles that the companies can charge a higher price for are those being recalled, which implies a lower over pricing environment for the car rental players. We view the trend of lower pricing and volume as consistent across the travel sector given hotel repair came in down \(5\%\) in July and both hotel and airport volume declined YoY in 2Q25.
